    <text>
        <body>
            <p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Charleston, So. Ca.</placeName>
                <date>Nov. 9. 1855</date>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>,
                    <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Dear Sir/ My sister-in-law,<lb/>
                <persName>Mrs. J. I. Moses</persName>, who is again with us in
                    <placeName>Charleston</placeName>, requests<lb/> me to ask you for the bill, and
                inform you that she wishes<lb/> the <hi rend="underline">Occident</hi> henceforth to
                be sent her to my care. The <date>November</date><lb/> No. you undoubtedly sent to
                    <placeName>N. York</placeName>, where it did no more<lb/> find her, as she left
                that city on the <date>31 of Oct.</date> last.</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Well, the <placeName>Cleveland</placeName>
                <hi rend="underline">Farce</hi> is over,<lb/> and, I doubt not, will be followed by
                a Tragedy, as, in my<lb/> humble opinion, the Reform gentlemen that were there,
                are<lb/> now dead.</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">I was <hi rend="underline">dangerously</hi> ill, and am<lb/> not yet
                permitted to labor as I am accustomed, or would<lb/> wish to do. On
                    <date>Monday</date> night, <date>22 Oct</date>, my life was for several<lb/>
                hours despaired of; I had the severest possible attack of In-<lb/>flammation of the
                bowels &amp; the stomach at the same time.<lb/> You must, therefore, excuse this
                brief letter.</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Yours, as ever,</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Most respectfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <persName role="author">Dr M Mayer</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
